# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: irradiance-volumes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Areas that lie outside of the ceiling lamp's direct light lack definition.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] For example, the lamp's housing appears completely uniform.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Without the ambient light added into the render, it would appear uniformly black.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Light is reflected by surfaces, and colored light transfers from one surface to another.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Notice how color from the red wall and green wall (not visible) reflects onto other surfaces in the scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] projected onto the red wall from light passing through the glass sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Theoretically, reflections, refractions, transparency, and shadows are all examples of global illumination, because when simulating them, one object affects the rendering of another (as opposed to an object being affected only by a direct source of light).
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] In practice, however, only the simulation of diffuse inter-reflection or caustics is called global illumination, especially in real-time settings.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Global illumination is a key aspect to the realism of a 3D scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Naive 3D lighting will only take into account direct light, meaning any light which radiates off a light source and bounces directly into the virtual camera.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Shadows will appear completely dark, due to light not interacting with any other surface before it reaches the camera.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] As this is not what occurs in real life, we perceive the resulting image as incomplete.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Applying full global illumination allows for the missing effects that makes an image feel more natural.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] However, global illumination is computationally more expensive and consequently much slower to generate.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] The algorithms used to calculate the distribution of light energy between surfaces of a scene are closely related to heat transfer simulations performed using finite-element methods in engineering design.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Achieving accurate computation of global illumination in real-time remains difficult.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] On one end, the diffuse inter-reflection component of global illumination is sometimes approximated by an "ambient" term in the lighting equation, which is also called "ambient lighting" or "ambient color" in 3D software.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Though this method is one of the cheapest ways to simulate indirect lighting, when used alone it does not provide an adequately realistic effect.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Ambient lighting is known to "flatten" shadows in 3D scenes, making the overall visual effect more bland.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Beyond ambient lighting, techniques which trace the path of light accurately have historically been either too slow for consumer hardware or limited to static and precomputed environments.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] This proves problematic, as most applications allow for input from a user that can affect their surroundings, and the precalculation steps may introduce constraints upon the artists.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Consequently, research has been dedicated to finding a balance between adequate performance, accurate visual results, and interactivity.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Starting with Nvidia's RTX 20 series, consumer graphics hardware has been extended to allow for ray tracing computations to be performed in real time through hardware acceleration.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] This has allowed for further improvements, as applications can now harness the power of this acceleration to provide not only precise lighting results, but the ability to affect said lighting dynamically.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Some content that has taken advantage of this capability includes Cyberpunk 2077, Indiana Jones and the Great Circle, and Alan Wake 2, among others.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] For an overview of the current state of real-time global illumination, see or.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Algorithms which attempt to simulate global illumination are numerical approximations of the rendering equation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/global-illumination] Well-known algorithms for computing global illumination include path tracing, photon mapping and radiosity.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:irradiance-volumes/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] A **light field**, or **lightfield**, is a physical field that describes the amount of light flowing in every direction through every point in a three-dimensional space.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The mathematical space of all possible light rays is given by the five-dimensional **plenoptic function** (with three position coordinates and two direction angles as arguments), and the magnitude of each ray is given by its radiance.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Michael Faraday was the first to propose that light should be interpreted as a field, much like the magnetic fields on which he had been working.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The term *light field* was coined by Andrey Gershun in a classic 1936 paper on the radiometric properties of light in three-dimensional space.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The term "radiance field" may also be used to refer to similar, or identical concepts.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The term is used in modern research such as neural radiance fields.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] For geometric optics—i.e., in the regime of incoherent light and objects larger than the wavelength of light—the fundamental carrier of light is a ray.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The measure for the amount of light traveling along a ray is radiance, denoted by *L* and expressed in units of W·sr−1·m−2; i.e., watts (W) per steradian (sr) per square meter (m2).
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The steradian is a measure of solid angle, and meters squared are used as a measure of cross-sectional area, as shown at right.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The radiance along all such rays in a region of three-dimensional space illuminated by an unchanging arrangement of lights is called the plenoptic function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The plenoptic illumination function is an idealized function used in computer vision and computer graphics to express the image of a scene from any possible viewing position at any viewing angle at any point in time.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] It is not used in practice computationally, but is conceptually useful in understanding other concepts in vision and graphics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Since rays in space can be parameterized by three coordinates, *x*, *y*, and *z* and two angles *θ* and *ϕ*, as shown at left, it is a five-dimensional function, that is, a function over a five-dimensional manifold equivalent to the product of 3D Euclidean space and the 2-sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The light field at each point in space can be treated as an infinite collection of vectors, one per direction impinging on the point, with lengths proportional to their radiances.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Integrating these vectors over any collection of lights, or over the entire sphere of directions, produces a vector-valued function of 3D space called the **vector irradiance field**.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The vector direction at each point in the field can be interpreted as the orientation of a flat surface placed at that point to most brightly illuminate it.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The vector magnitude is a scalar-valued function of 3D space, called the **irradiance**.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Time, wavelength, and polarization angle can be treated as additional dimensions, yielding higher-dimensional functions, accordingly.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] In a plenoptic function, if the region of interest contains a concave object (e.g., a cupped hand), then light leaving one point on the object may travel only a short distance before another point on the object blocks it.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] No practical device could measure the function in such a region.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] However, for locations outside the object's convex hull (e.g., shrink-wrap), the plenoptic function can be measured by capturing multiple images.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] In this case the function contains redundant information, because the radiance along a ray remains constant throughout its length.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The redundant information is exactly one dimension, leaving a four-dimensional function variously termed the photic field, the 4D light field or lumigraph.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Formally, the field is defined as radiance along rays in empty space.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The set of rays in a light field can be parameterized in a variety of ways.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The most common is the two-plane parameterization.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] While this parameterization cannot represent all rays, for example rays parallel to the two planes if the planes are parallel to each other, it relates closely to the analytic geometry of perspective imaging.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] A simple way to think about a two-plane light field is as a collection of perspective images of the *st* plane (and any objects that may lie astride or beyond it), each taken from an observer position on the *uv* plane.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] A light field parameterized this way is sometimes called a light slab.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The analog of the 4D light field for sound is the sound field or wave field*,* as in wave field synthesis, and the corresponding parametrization is the Kirchhoff–Helmholtz integral, which states that, in the absence of obstacles, a sound field over time is given by the pressure on a plane.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Thus this is two dimensions of information at any point in time, and over time, a 3D field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] However, light travelling in non-vacuous media may scatter in a similar fashion, and the irreversibility or information lost in the scattering is discernible in the apparent loss of a system dimension.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Because light field provides spatial and angular information, we can alter the position of focal planes after exposure, which is often termed *refocusing*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The principle of refocusing is to obtain conventional 2-D photographs from a light field through the integral transform.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The transform takes a lightfield as its input and generates a photograph focused on a specific plane.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Another problem is high computational complexity.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] To compute an $N\times N$ 2-D photograph from an $N\times N\times N\times N$ 4-D light field, the complexity of the formula is $O(N^{4})$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] One way to reduce the complexity of computation is to adopt the concept of Fourier slice theorem: The photography operator ${\mathcal {P}}_{\alpha }\left[\cdot \right]$ can be viewed as a shear followed by projection.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The result should be proportional to a dilated 2-D slice of the 4-D Fourier transform of a light field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] More precisely, a refocused image can be generated from the 4-D Fourier spectrum of a light field by extracting a 2-D slice, applying an inverse 2-D transform, and scaling.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The asymptotic complexity of the algorithm is $O(N^{2}\operatorname {log} N)$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Another way to efficiently compute 2-D photographs is to adopt discrete focal stack transform (DFST).
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] DFST is designed to generate a collection of refocused 2-D photographs, or so-called Focal Stack.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] This method can be implemented by fast fractional fourier transform (FrFT).
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Because $({\boldsymbol {u}}q+{\boldsymbol {s}},{\boldsymbol {u}})$ is usually not on the 4-D grid, DFST adopts trigonometric interpolation to compute the non-grid values.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] In computer graphics, light fields are typically produced either by rendering a 3D model or by photographing a real scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] In either case, to produce a light field, views must be obtained for a large collection of viewpoints.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Depending on the parameterization, this collection typically spans some portion of a line, circle, plane, sphere, or other shape, although unstructured collections are possible.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Devices for capturing light fields photographically may include a moving handheld camera or a robotically controlled camera, an arc of cameras (as in the bullet time effect used in *The Matrix*), a dense array of cameras, handheld cameras, microscopes, or other optical system.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The number of images in a light field depends on the application.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] A light field capture of Michelangelo's statue of *Night* contains 24,000 1.3-megapixel images, which is considered large as of 2022.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] For light field rendering to completely capture an opaque object, images must be taken of at least the front and back.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Less obviously, for an object that lies astride the *st* plane, finely spaced images must be taken on the *uv* plane (in the two-plane parameterization shown above).
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The number and arrangement of images in a light field, and the resolution of each image, are together called the "sampling" of the 4D light field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Also of interest are the effects of occlusion, lighting and reflection.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Gershun's reason for studying the light field was to derive (in closed form) illumination patterns that would be observed on surfaces due to light sources of various shapes positioned above these surface.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The branch of optics devoted to illumination engineering is nonimaging optics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] It extensively uses the concept of flow lines (Gershun's flux lines) and vector flux (Gershun's light vector).
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] However, the light field (in this case the positions and directions defining the light rays) is commonly described in terms of phase space and Hamiltonian optics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Extracting appropriate 2D slices from the 4D light field of a scene, enables novel views of the scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Depending on the parameterization of the light field and slices, these views might be perspective, orthographic, crossed-slit, general linear cameras, multi-perspective, or another type of projection.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Light field rendering is one form of image-based rendering.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Integrating an appropriate 4D subset of the samples in a light field can approximate the view that would be captured by a camera having a finite (i.e., non-pinhole) aperture.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Such a view has a finite depth of field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Shearing or warping the light field before performing this integration can focus on different fronto-parallel or oblique planes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Images captured by digital cameras that capture the light field can be refocused.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Presenting a light field using technology that maps each sample to the appropriate ray in physical space produces an autostereoscopic visual effect akin to viewing the original scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Non-digital technologies for doing this include integral photography, parallax panoramagrams, and holography; digital technologies include placing an array of lenslets over a high-resolution display screen, or projecting the imagery onto an array of lenslets using an array of video projectors.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] An array of video cameras can capture and display a time-varying light field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] This essentially constitutes a 3D television system.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Modern approaches to light-field display explore co-designs of optical elements and compressive computation to achieve higher resolutions, increased contrast, wider fields of view, and other benefits.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Neural activity can be recorded optically by genetically encoding neurons with reversible fluorescent markers such as GCaMP that indicate the presence of calcium ions in real time.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Since light field microscopy captures full volume information in a single frame, it is possible to monitor neural activity in individual neurons randomly distributed in a large volume at video framerate.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Quantitative measurement of neural activity can be done despite optical aberrations in brain tissue and without reconstructing a volume image, and be used to monitor activity in thousands of neurons.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] This is a method of creating and/or refining a scene model representing a generalized light field and a relightable matter field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Data used in reconstruction includes images, video, object models, and/or scene models.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The generalized light field represents light flowing in the scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The relightable matter field represents the light interaction properties and emissivity of matter occupying the scene.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Scene data structures can be implemented using Neural Networks, and Physics-based structures, among others.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] The light and matter fields are at least partially disentangled.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Image generation and predistortion of synthetic imagery for holographic stereograms is one of the earliest examples of computed light fields.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Glare arises due to multiple scattering of light inside the camera body and lens optics that reduces image contrast.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] While glare has been analyzed in 2D image space, it is useful to identify it as a 4D ray-space phenomenon.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Statistically analyzing the ray-space inside a camera allows the classification and removal of glare artifacts.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] In ray-space, glare behaves as high frequency noise and can be reduced by outlier rejection.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Such analysis can be performed by capturing the light field inside the camera, but it results in the loss of spatial resolution.
[src:irradiance-volumes/light-field] Uniform and non-uniform ray sampling can be used to reduce glare without significantly compromising image resolution.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In mathematics and physical science, **spherical harmonics** are special functions defined on the surface of a sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are often employed in solving partial differential equations in many scientific fields.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The table of spherical harmonics contains a list of common spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since the spherical harmonics form a complete set of orthogonal functions and thus an orthonormal basis, certain functions defined on the surface of a sphere can be written as a sum of these spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is similar to periodic functions defined on a circle that can be expressed as a sum of circular functions (sines and cosines) via Fourier series.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Like the sines and cosines in Fourier series, the spherical harmonics may be organized by (spatial) angular frequency, as seen in the rows of functions in the illustration on the right.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Further, spherical harmonics are basis functions for irreducible representations of SO(3), the group of rotations in three dimensions, and thus play a central role in the group theoretic discussion of SO(3).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics originate from solving Laplace's equation in the spherical domains.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Functions that are solutions to Laplace's equation are called harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Despite their name, spherical harmonics take their simplest form in Cartesian coordinates, where they can be defined as homogeneous polynomials of degree $\ell$ in $(x,y,z)$ that obey Laplace's equation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In this setting, they may be viewed as the angular portion of a set of solutions to Laplace's equation in three dimensions, and this viewpoint is often taken as an alternative definition.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics, as functions on the sphere, are eigenfunctions of the Laplace-Beltrami operator (see Higher dimensions).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] A specific set of spherical harmonics, denoted $Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ or $Y_{\ell }^{m}({\mathbf {r} })$ , are known as Laplace's spherical harmonics, as they were first introduced by Pierre Simon de Laplace in 1782.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions form an orthogonal system, and are thus basic to the expansion of a general function on the sphere as alluded to above.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 3D computer graphics, spherical harmonics play a role in a wide variety of topics including indirect lighting (ambient occlusion, global illumination, precomputed radiance transfer, etc.) and modelling of 3D shapes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics were first investigated in connection with the Newtonian potential of Newton's law of universal gravitation in three dimensions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Each term in the above summation is an individual Newtonian potential for a point mass.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Just prior to that time, Adrien-Marie Legendre had investigated the expansion of the Newtonian potential in powers of *r* = |**x**| and *r*1 = |**x**1|.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] where *γ* is the angle between the vectors **x** and **x**1.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The functions $P_{i}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ are the Legendre polynomials, and they can be derived as a special case of spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Subsequently, in his 1782 memoir, Laplace investigated these coefficients using spherical coordinates to represent the angle *γ* between **x**1 and **x**.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 1867, William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) and Peter Guthrie Tait introduced the solid spherical harmonics in their *Treatise on Natural Philosophy*, and also first introduced the name of "spherical harmonics" for these functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The 19th century development of Fourier series made possible the solution of a wide variety of physical problems in rectangular domains, such as the solution of the heat equation and wave equation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This could be achieved by expansion of functions in series of trigonometric functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Whereas the trigonometric functions in a Fourier series represent the fundamental modes of vibration in a string, the spherical harmonics represent the fundamental modes of vibration of a sphere in much the same way.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many aspects of the theory of Fourier series could be generalized by taking expansions in spherical harmonics rather than trigonometric functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Moreover, analogous to how trigonometric functions can equivalently be written as complex exponentials, spherical harmonics also possessed an equivalent form as complex-valued functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This was a boon for problems possessing spherical symmetry, such as those of celestial mechanics originally studied by Laplace and Legendre.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The prevalence of spherical harmonics already in physics set the stage for their later importance in the 20th century birth of quantum mechanics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The (complex-valued) spherical harmonics $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ are eigenfunctions of the square of the orbital angular momentum operator $-i\hbar \mathbf {r} \times \nabla ,$ and therefore they represent the different quantized configurations of atomic orbitals.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Laplace's equation imposes that the Laplacian of a scalar field *f* is zero.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] A priori, *m* is a complex constant, but because Φ must be a periodic function whose period evenly divides 2*π*, *m* is necessarily an integer and Φ is a linear combination of the complex exponentials *e*± *imφ*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The solution function *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is regular at the poles of the sphere, where *θ* = 0, *π*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Furthermore, a change of variables *t* = cos *θ* transforms this equation into the Legendre equation, whose solution is a multiple of the associated Legendre polynomial *Pm ℓ*(cos *θ*) .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, the equation for *R* has solutions of the form *R*(*r*) = *A rℓ* + *B r*−*ℓ* − 1; requiring the solution to be regular throughout **R**3 forces *B* = 0.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here the solution was assumed to have the special form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For a given value of *ℓ*, there are 2*ℓ* + 1 independent solutions of this form, one for each integer *m* with −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ is called a **spherical harmonic function of degree *ℓ* and order *m***, $P_{\ell }^{m}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ is an associated Legendre polynomial, *N* is a normalization constant, and *θ* and *φ* represent colatitude and longitude, respectively.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, the colatitude *θ*, or polar angle, ranges from *0* at the North Pole, to *π*/2 at the Equator, to *π* at the South Pole, and the longitude *φ*, or azimuth, may assume all values with 0 ≤ *φ* < 2*π*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In fact, for any such solution, *rℓ Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is the expression in spherical coordinates of a homogeneous polynomial $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ that is harmonic (see below), and so counting dimensions shows that there are 2*ℓ* + 1 linearly independent such polynomials.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] where the $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ are constants and the factors *rℓ Yℓm* are known as (*regular*) solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $r>R$ , the solid harmonics with negative powers of r (the *irregular* solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\setminus \{\mathbf {0} \}\to \mathbb {C}$ ) are chosen instead.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In that case, one needs to expand the solution of known regions in Laurent series (about $r=\infty$ ), instead of the Taylor series (about $r=0$ ) used above, to match the terms and find series expansion coefficients $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If *Y* is a joint eigenfunction of **L**2 and *L**z*, then by definition ${\begin{aligned}\mathbf {L} ^{2}Y&=\lambda Y\\L_{z}Y&=mY\end{aligned}}$ for some real numbers *m* and *λ*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here *m* must in fact be an integer, for *Y* must be periodic in the coordinate *φ* with period a number that evenly divides 2*π*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, *L**k* + : *E**λ*,*m* → *E**λ*,*m*+*k* must be zero for *k* sufficiently large, because the inequality *λ* ≥ *m*2 must hold in each of the nontrivial joint eigenspaces.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The foregoing has been all worked out in the spherical coordinate representation, $\langle \theta ,\varphi |lm\rangle =Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ but may be expressed more abstractly in the complete, orthonormal spherical ket basis.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics can be expressed as the restriction to the unit sphere of certain polynomial functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Specifically, we say that a (complex-valued) polynomial function $p:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ is *homogeneous* of degree $\ell$ if $p(\lambda \mathbf {x} )=\lambda ^{\ell }p(\mathbf {x} )$ for all real numbers $\lambda \in \mathbb {R}$ and all $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] We say that p is *harmonic* if $\Delta p=0,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplacian.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, when $\ell =1$ , $\mathbf {A} _{1}$ is just the 3-dimensional space of all linear functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , since any such function is automatically harmonic.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For any $\ell$ , the space $\mathbf {H} _{\ell }$ of spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ is just the space of restrictions to the sphere $S^{2}$ of the elements of $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] As suggested in the introduction, this perspective is presumably the origin of the term "spherical harmonic" (i.e., the restriction to the sphere of a harmonic function).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, for any $c\in \mathbb {C}$ the formula $p(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=c(x_{1}+ix_{2})^{\ell }$ defines a homogeneous polynomial of degree $\ell$ with domain and codomain $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , which happens to be independent of $x_{3}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This polynomial is easily seen to be harmonic.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] One source of confusion with the definition of the spherical harmonic functions concerns a phase factor of $(-1)^{m}$ , commonly referred to as the Condon–Shortley phase in the quantum mechanical literature.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This phase factor may be included either in the definition of the associated Legendre polynomials or in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but it should not be counted twice.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Some authors instead define associated Legendre functions without this phase factor.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] There is no requirement to use the Condon–Shortley phase in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but including it can simplify some quantum mechanical operations, especially the application of raising and lowering operators.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The geodesy and magnetics communities commonly use conventions in which the Condon–Shortley phase factor is not included in the associated Legendre functions or in the spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Several different normalizations are in common use for the Laplace spherical harmonic functions $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These normalization choices are independent of the placement of the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The disciplines of geodesy and spectral analysis often use the corresponding $4\pi$ -normalized harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The magnetics community, in contrast, often uses Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the phase convention used in this article, the complex spherical harmonics satisfy $Y_{\ell }^{m}{}^{*}(\theta ,\varphi )=(-1)^{m}Y_{\ell }^{-m}(\theta ,\varphi ),$ where the superscript * denotes complex conjugation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This equation also follows from the relation of the spherical harmonic functions with the Wigner D-matrix.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ are sometimes known as *tesseral spherical harmonics*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions have the same orthonormality properties as the complex ones $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ above.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}$ with *m* > 0 are said to be of cosine type, and those with *m* < 0 of sine type.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] With a different placement of that phase, the displayed signs must be changed consistently.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The same sine and cosine factors can be also seen in the following subsection that deals with the Cartesian representation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] See here for a list of real spherical harmonics up to and including $\ell =4$ , which can be seen to be consistent with the output of the equations above.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] From the analytic solutions for the hydrogen atom, the eigenfunctions of the angular part of the wave function are spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, the solutions of the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation without magnetic terms can be made real.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is why the real forms are extensively used in basis functions for quantum chemistry, as the programs do not then need to use complex algebra.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here, the real functions span the same space as the complex ones would.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, as can be seen from the table of spherical harmonics, the usual *p* functions ( $\ell =1$ ) are complex and mix axis directions, but the real versions are essentially just *x*, *y*, and *z*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] More specifically, it is the (unique up to normalization) Gelfand-Tsetlin-basis of this representation of the rotational group $SO(3)$ and an explicit formula for $R_{\ell }^{m}$ in cartesian coordinates can be derived from that fact.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] It suffices to take v and $\lambda$ as real parameters.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In naming this generating function after Herglotz, we follow Courant & Hilbert 1962, §VII.7, who credit unpublished notes by him for its discovery.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Essentially all the properties of the spherical harmonics can be derived from this generating function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are, moreover, a standardized set with a fixed scale or normalization.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The factor ${\bar {\Pi }}_{\ell }^{m}(z)$ is essentially the associated Legendre polynomial $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ , and the factors $(A_{m}\pm iB_{m})$ are essentially $e^{\pm im\varphi }$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have deep and consequential properties under the operations of spatial inversion (parity) and rotation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have definite parity.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] That is, they are either even or odd with respect to inversion about the origin.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Inversion is represented by the operator $P\Psi (\mathbf {r} )=\Psi (-\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In terms of the spherical angles, parity transforms a point with coordinates $\{\theta ,\varphi \}$ to $\{\pi -\theta ,\pi +\varphi \}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Parity continues to hold for real spherical harmonics, and for spherical harmonics in higher dimensions: applying a point reflection to a spherical harmonic of degree ℓ changes the sign by a factor of (−1)*ℓ*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Consider a rotation ${\mathcal {R}}$ about the origin that sends the unit vector $\mathbf {r}$ to $\mathbf {r} '$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Under this operation, a spherical harmonic of degree $\ell$ and order m transforms into a linear combination of spherical harmonics of the same degree.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, this is not the standard way of expressing this property.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The rotational behavior of the spherical harmonics is perhaps their quintessential feature from the viewpoint of group theory.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ 's of degree $\ell$ provide a basis set of functions for the irreducible representation of the group SO(3) of dimension $(2\ell +1)$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many facts about spherical harmonics (such as the addition theorem) that are proved laboriously using the methods of analysis acquire simpler proofs and deeper significance using the methods of symmetry.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {C} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The expansion coefficients are the analogs of Fourier coefficients, and can be obtained by multiplying the above equation by the complex conjugate of a spherical harmonic, integrating over the solid angle Ω, and utilizing the above orthogonality relationships.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is justified rigorously by basic Hilbert space theory.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the coefficients decay in *ℓ* sufficiently rapidly — for instance, exponentially — then the series also converges uniformly to *f*.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The convergence of the series holds again in the same sense, namely the real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {R} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The completeness relation is a distributional equality between a sum over all indices and the Dirac delta function.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the spherical harmonics, the Dirac delta is the tensor product of two Dirac delta functions, one for the azimuthal angle on the sphere, and one for the polar angle.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The total power of a function *f* is defined in the signal processing literature as the integral of the function squared, divided by the area of its domain.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] is defined as the angular power spectrum (for Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the functions *f* and *g* have a zero mean (i.e., the spectral coefficients *f*00 and *g*00 are zero), then *S**ff*(*ℓ*) and *S**fg*(*ℓ*) represent the contributions to the function's variance and covariance for degree ℓ, respectively.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* = 0, the spectrum is "white" as each degree possesses equal power.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* < 0, the spectrum is termed "red" as there is more power at the low degrees with long wavelengths than higher degrees.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, when *β* > 0, the spectrum is termed "blue".
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The condition on the order of growth of *S**ff*(*ℓ*) is related to the order of differentiability of *f* in the next section.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics are used to approximate functions on the sphere, and the order of decay of the power governs smoothness.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Let $\Pi _{n}(S^{2})$ denote the space spanned by spherical harmonics of degree at most n .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] with the norm taken in $L^{p}(S^{2})$ , or in the uniform norm when $p=\infty$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The asymptotic behavior of $E_{n}(f)_{p}$ as $n\to \infty$ gives a quantitative measure of how well f can be approximated by low-degree spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is analogous to approximation by trigonometric polynomials in ordinary Fourier analysis.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the circle, smoothness can be measured by the decay of Fourier coefficients.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the sphere, smoother functions admit faster approximation by spherical polynomials, while conversely, sufficiently rapid decay of the approximation error implies smoothness.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] More precisely, Sobolev-type smoothness can also be described spectrally, since spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ are eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator with eigenvalue $-\ell (\ell +1)$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $p=2$ this relation can be stated especially explicitly.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus $f\in H^{s}(S^{2})$ precisely when this weighted sum is finite.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since $\ell (\ell +1)$ grows like $\ell ^{2}$ , higher Sobolev smoothness requires faster decay of the power in high degrees.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] which bounds the approximation error by the Sobolev norm.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] With the above power normalization, a decay estimate of the form $S_{ff}(\ell )=O(\ell ^{-\alpha })$ implies membership in $H^{s}(S^{2})$ whenever $\alpha >2s+1$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus sufficiently fast polynomial decay of the power spectrum implies differentiability, and decay faster than every power implies smoothness of all orders.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] A mathematical result of considerable interest and use is called the *addition theorem* for spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] where *P**ℓ* is the Legendre polynomial of degree ℓ.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] This expression is valid for both real and complex harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The result can be proven analytically, using the properties of the Poisson kernel in the unit ball, or geometrically by applying a rotation to the vector **y** so that it points along the *z*-axis, and then directly calculating the right-hand side.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] In the expansion (**1**), the left-hand side $P_{\ell }(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} )$ is a constant multiple of the degree ℓ zonal spherical harmonic.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] From this perspective, one has the following generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let *Y**j* be an arbitrary orthonormal basis of the space **H***ℓ* of degree ℓ spherical harmonics on the n-sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Combining (**2**) and (**3**) gives (**1**) in dimension *n* = 2 when **x** and **y** are represented in spherical coordinates.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The values of c and $\gamma$ that result in non-zero terms in this sum are determined by the selection rules for the 3j-symbols.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are the coefficients appearing in the expansion of the product of two spherical harmonics in terms of spherical harmonics themselves.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] A variety of techniques are available for doing essentially the same calculation, including the Wigner 3-jm symbol, the Racah coefficients, and the Slater integrals.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Abstractly, the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients express the tensor product of two irreducible representations of the rotation group as a sum of irreducible representations: suitably normalized, the coefficients are then the multiplicities.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ can be visualized by considering their "nodal lines", that is, the set of points on the sphere where $\Re [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ , or alternatively where $\Im [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Nodal lines of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ are composed of *ℓ* circles: there are |*m*| circles along longitudes and *ℓ*−|*m*| circles along latitudes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] One can determine the number of nodal lines of each type by counting the number of zeros of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ in the $\theta$ and $\varphi$ directions respectively.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\theta$ , the real and imaginary components of the associated Legendre polynomials each possess *ℓ*−|*m*| zeros, each giving rise to a nodal 'line of latitude'.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] On the other hand, considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\varphi$ , the trigonometric sin and cos functions possess 2|*m*| zeros, each of which gives rise to a nodal 'line of longitude'.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] When the spherical harmonic order *m* is zero (upper-left in the figure), the spherical harmonic functions do not depend upon longitude, and are referred to as ***zonal***.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Such spherical harmonics are a special case of zonal spherical functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] When *ℓ* = |*m*| (bottom-right in the figure), there are no zero crossings in latitude, and the functions are referred to as ***sectoral***.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] For the other cases, the functions checker the sphere, and they are referred to as ***tesseral***.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More general spherical harmonics of degree ℓ are not necessarily those of the Laplace basis $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ , and their nodal sets can be of a fairly general kind.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The classical spherical harmonics are defined as complex-valued functions on the unit sphere $S^{2}$ inside three-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as follows, leading to functions $S^{n-1}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **P***ℓ* denote the space of complex-valued homogeneous polynomials of degree ℓ in n real variables, here considered as functions $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **A***ℓ* denote the subspace of **P***ℓ* consisting of all harmonic polynomials: $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }:=\{p\in \mathbf {P} _{\ell }\,\mid \,\Delta p=0\}\,.$ These are the (regular) solid spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics of degree ℓ is a representation of the symmetry group of rotations around a point (SO(3)) and its double-cover SU(2).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Indeed, rotations act on the two-dimensional sphere, and thus also on **H***ℓ* by function composition $\psi \mapsto \psi \circ \rho ^{-1}$ for ψ a spherical harmonic and ρ a rotation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The representation **H***ℓ* is an irreducible representation of SO(3).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The elements of **H***ℓ* arise as the restrictions to the sphere of elements of **A***ℓ*: harmonic polynomials homogeneous of degree ℓ on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Thus as an irreducible representation of SO(3), **H***ℓ* is isomorphic to the space of traceless symmetric tensors of degree ℓ.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, the analogous statements hold in higher dimensions: the space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics on the n-sphere is the irreducible representation of SO(*n*+1) corresponding to the traceless symmetric ℓ-tensors.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] However, whereas every irreducible tensor representation of SO(2) and SO(3) is of this kind, the special orthogonal groups in higher dimensions have additional irreducible representations that do not arise in this manner.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The special orthogonal groups have additional spin representations that are not tensor representations, and are *typically* not spherical harmonics.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] An exception are the spin representation of SO(3): strictly speaking these are representations of the double cover SU(2) of SO(3).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] In turn, SU(2) is identified with the group of unit quaternions, and so coincides with the 3-sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The spaces of spherical harmonics on the 3-sphere are certain spin representations of SO(3), with respect to the action by quaternionic multiplication.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be separated into two sets of functions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] One is hemispherical harmonics (HSH), orthogonal and complete on hemisphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Another is complementary hemispherical harmonics (CHSH).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The angle-preserving symmetries of the two-sphere are described by the group of Möbius transformations PSL(2,**C**).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] With respect to this group, the sphere is equivalent to the usual Riemann sphere.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The group PSL(2,**C**) is isomorphic to the (proper) Lorentz group, and its action on the two-sphere agrees with the action of the Lorentz group on the celestial sphere in Minkowski space.
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The analog of the spherical harmonics for the Lorentz group is given by the hypergeometric series; furthermore, the spherical harmonics can be re-expressed in terms of the hypergeometric series, as SO(3) = PSU(2) is a subgroup of PSL(2,**C**).
[src:irradiance-volumes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, hypergeometric series can be generalized to describe the symmetries of any symmetric space; in particular, hypergeometric series can be developed for any Lie group.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] In scientific visualization and computer graphics, **volume rendering** is a set of techniques used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set, typically a 3D scalar field.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT, MRI, or MicroCT scanner.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice for each millimeter of depth) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] To render a 2D projection of the 3D data set, one first needs to define a camera in space relative to the volume.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Also, one needs to define the opacity and color of every voxel.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This is usually defined using an RGBA (for red, green, blue, alpha) transfer function that defines the RGBA value for every possible voxel value.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] For example, a volume may be viewed by extracting isosurfaces (surfaces of equal values) from the volume and rendering them as polygonal meshes or by rendering the volume directly as a block of data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The marching cubes algorithm is a common technique for extracting an isosurface from volume data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Direct volume rendering is a computationally intensive task that may be performed in several ways.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Another method of volume rendering is Ray marching, a category of 3D computer graphics rendering techniques in which rays are traced step by step, subdividing each ray into smaller segments and sampling a function at each interval.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Volume rendering is distinguished from thin slice tomography presentations, and is also generally distinguished from projections of 3D models, including maximum intensity projection.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Still, technically, all volume renderings become projections when viewed on a 2-dimensional display, making the distinction between projections and volume renderings a bit vague.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Nevertheless, the epitomes of volume rendering models feature a mix of for example coloring and shading in order to create realistic and/or observable representations.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] A direct volume renderer requires every sample value to be mapped to opacity and a color.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This is done with a "transfer function" which can be a simple ramp, a piecewise linear function or an arbitrary table.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Once converted to an RGBA color model (for red, green, blue, alpha) value, the composed RGBA result is projected on the corresponding pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The way this is done depends on the rendering technique.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] A combination of these techniques is possible.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] For instance, a shear warp implementation could use texturing hardware to draw the aligned slices in the off-screen buffer.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The technique of volume ray casting can be derived directly from the rendering equation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] It provides results of very high quality, usually considered to provide the best image quality.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Volume ray casting is classified as image based volume rendering technique, as the computation emanates from the output image, not the input volume data as is the case with object based techniques.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] In this technique, a ray is generated for each desired image pixel.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Using a simple camera model, the ray starts at the center of projection of the camera (usually the eye point) and passes through the image pixel on the imaginary image plane floating in between the camera and the volume to be rendered.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The ray is clipped by the boundaries of the volume in order to save time.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Then the ray is sampled at regular or adaptive intervals throughout the volume.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The data is interpolated at each sample point, the transfer function applied to form an RGBA sample, the sample is composited onto the accumulated RGBA of the ray, and the process repeated until the ray exits the volume.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The RGBA color is converted to an RGB color and deposited in the corresponding image pixel.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The process is repeated for every pixel on the screen to form the completed image.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This is a technique which trades quality for speed.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Here, every volume element is splatted, as Lee Westover said, like a snow ball, on to the viewing surface in back to front order.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] These splats are rendered as disks whose properties (color and transparency) vary diametrically in normal (Gaussian) manner.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Flat disks and those with other kinds of property distribution are also used depending on the application.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The shear warp approach to volume rendering was developed by Cameron and Undrill, popularized by Philippe Lacroute and Marc Levoy.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] In this technique, the viewing transformation is transformed such that the nearest face of the volume becomes axis aligned with an off-screen image data buffer with a fixed scale of voxels to pixels.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The volume is then rendered into this buffer using the far more favorable memory alignment and fixed scaling and blending factors.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Once all slices of the volume have been rendered, the buffer is then warped into the desired orientation and scaled in the displayed image.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This technique is relatively fast in software at the cost of less accurate sampling and potentially worse image quality compared to ray casting.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] There is memory overhead for storing multiple copies of the volume, for the ability to have near axis aligned volumes.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This overhead can be mitigated using run-length encoding.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Many 3D graphics systems use texture mapping to apply images, or textures, to geometric objects.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Commodity PC graphics cards are fast at texturing and can efficiently render slices of a 3D volume, with real time interaction capabilities.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Workstation GPUs are even faster, and are the basis for much of the production volume visualization used in medical imaging, oil and gas, and other markets (2007).
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] In earlier years, dedicated 3D texture mapping systems were used on graphics systems such as Silicon Graphics InfiniteReality, HP Visualize FX graphics accelerator, and others.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This technique was first described by Bill Hibbard and Dave Santek.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] These slices can either be aligned with the volume and rendered at an angle to the viewer, or aligned with the viewing plane and sampled from unaligned slices through the volume.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Graphics hardware support for 3D textures is needed for the second technique.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Volume aligned texturing produces images of reasonable quality.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The image quality degrades with coarse slice counts, though there is often a noticeable transition when the volume is rotated.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Due to the extremely parallel nature of direct volume rendering, special purpose volume rendering hardware was a rich research topic before GPU volume rendering became fast enough.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The most widely cited technology was the VolumePro real-time ray-casting system, developed by Hanspeter Pfister and scientists at Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, which used high memory bandwidth and brute force to render using the ray casting algorithm.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The technology was transferred to TeraRecon, Inc. and two generations of ASICs were produced and sold.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Pixel shaders are able to read and write randomly from video memory and perform some basic mathematical and logical calculations.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] These SIMD processors were used to perform general calculations such as rendering polygons and signal processing.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] In recent GPU generations, the pixel shaders now are able to function as MIMD processors (now able to independently branch) utilizing up to 1 GB of texture memory with floating point formats.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] With such power, virtually any algorithm with steps that can be performed in parallel, such as volume ray casting or tomographic reconstruction, can be performed with tremendous acceleration.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The programmable pixel shaders can be used to simulate variations in the characteristics of lighting, shadow, reflection, emissive color and so forth.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Such simulations can be written using high level shading languages.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The primary goal of optimization is to skip as much of the volume as possible.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] A typical medical data set can be 1 GB in size.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] To render that at 30 frame/s requires an extremely fast memory bus.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Skipping voxels means less information needs to be processed.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Often, a volume rendering system will have a system for identifying regions of the volume containing no visible material.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This information can be used to avoid rendering these transparent regions.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This is a technique used when the volume is rendered in front to back order.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] For a ray through a pixel, once sufficient dense material has been encountered, further samples will make no significant contribution to the pixel and so may be neglected.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The use of hierarchical structures such as octree and BSP-tree could be very helpful for both compression of volume data and speed optimization of volumetric ray casting process.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Image segmentation is a manual or automatic procedure that can be used to section out large portions of the volume that one considers uninteresting before rendering, the amount of calculations that have to be made by ray casting or texture blending can be significantly reduced.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This reduction can be as much as from O(n) to O(log n) for n sequentially indexed voxels.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation also has significant performance benefits for other ray tracing algorithms.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation can subsequently be used to highlight or expose structures of interest.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] By representing less interesting regions of the volume in a coarser resolution, the data input overhead can be reduced.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] On closer observation, the data in these regions can be populated either by reading from memory or disk, or by interpolation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The coarser resolution volume is resampled to a smaller size in the same way as a 2D mipmap image is created from the original.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] These smaller volume are also used by themselves while rotating the volume to a new orientation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Pre-integrated volume rendering is a method that can reduce sampling artifacts by pre-computing much of the required data.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] It is especially useful in hardware-accelerated applications because it improves quality without a large performance impact.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Unlike most other optimizations, this does not skip voxels.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Rather it reduces the number of samples needed to accurately display a region of voxels.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] The idea is to render the intervals between the samples instead of the samples themselves.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] This technique captures rapidly changing material, for example the transition from muscle to bone with much less computation.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models from 3D image data (such as MRI, CT, Industrial CT or microtomography) for computational analysis and design, e.g.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] For a complete display view, only one voxel per pixel (the front one) is required to be shown (although more can be used for smoothing the image), if animation is needed, the front voxels to be shown can be cached and their location relative to the camera can be recalculated as it moves.
[src:irradiance-volumes/volume-rendering] Where display voxels become too far apart to cover all the pixels, new front voxels can be found by ray casting or similar, and where two voxels are in one pixel, the front one can be kept.
